    "recap_headline": "Rutgers University",
    "recap_text": "PISCATAWAY, N.J. \u2013\nRutgers baseball won Sunday's game over Michigan State by a score of 8-6 to clinch the series.\nThe Scarlet Knights (11-8, 2-1) took a 2-1 lead in the\u00a0fourth and never looked back against the Spartans (5-13, 1-5), winning the opening series of Big Ten play for the first time since 2022.\nRyan Jaros\ndrove in three runs in the game, getting things started with a sac fly in the fourth and driving in two more on a bases-loaded single in the fifth.\nA double from\nQuinten Perilli\ngave RU a lead it would not relinquish in the fourth.\nChris Sand\nwas able to work around a solo homer in the second, making the start on the mound and battling through 3.1 innings with just one run allowed on four hits.\nJoe Mazza\nrelieved him, pitching 2.2 innings and giving up one run on two hits with two strikeouts.\nAndrew Rondini\npitched the seventh and eighth innings, striking out one with an unearned run crossing in the seventh.\nMSU battled back in the ninth, scoring three runs on a pair of doubles to make it a two-run game.\nJason Masick\nwas able to come in and get the last out to earn the save.\nWith the Scarlet Knights holding a 4-2 lead in the sixth,\nTrey Wells\nsingled in a run to make it 5-2. With the bases loaded,\nChase Krewson\nbeat out an infield to score one run and after he beat the throw to first, Wells caught the Spartan defense napping and scored to make it 7-2.\nThree RU players collected multiple hits, including a 3-for-5 day from\nYomar Carreras\n, his seventh multi-hit game of the season. Krewson (2) and Jaros (3) both collected multiple RBIs in the contest as well.\nRutgers wraps up its homestand with a midweek contest against Monmouth, set for 3 p.m. at Bainton Field on Tuesday.\nFollow Rutgers Baseball on Social Media\nX\n|\nInstagram\n|\nFacebook"
  },
